commit_list.message:
Improve qa's flakiness debugging tools

Fix tests to fail if watchman is killed

Fix local variable capture in cases where bindings
do not exactly match the exception backtrace.

Properly run tapjio.Visitor.End(error) at the
end of a test run.

Extract command line formatting into its own
file and type. This is so it can be reused
consistently across multiple commands.

Improve messaging around seeds used for multiple
test runs.

Add qa flaky top subcommand to replace the
previous qa flaky command. The new command
includes a much improved report format. Also
support an actual REPL for working with flaky
tests. This REPL is still a work in progress,
but it avoids reloading all events from the qa
archive each time the report is viewed or a test
is re-run.

Add qa flaky repro subcommand to reproduce a
specific flaky outcome and attach a pry-remote
session to it.

Add support for QA_ARCHIVE environment variable
to avoid needing to specify it for each command.

Move outcome digesting logic from Ruby into Go.
This was necessary to keep flaky outcome repro-
duction simple, but it's also a (small) step
towards support for other (non-Ruby) test
frameworks.

Errors now always capture locals, since we're
using the more stable binding_of_caller gem.

Add runtime dependencies to qa-tool gem. This
means that it's no longer safely distributable
as a tgz, since it has dependencies on other
ruby gems. For now we accept this limitation
as it keeps the build process simple and these
third-party dependencies provide a dramatically
better user experience

Update simple demo script:
- remove bundle install

Update flaky demo script:
- remove bundle install
- to exercise flaky outcome reproduction

commit_list.message:
Introducing the -watch option, and waaaay more!

So this commit is massive. Sorry about that. I got carried
away adding -watch support and ended up improving a lot of
other things along the way.

Current qa -watch features include runtime dependency analysis
of any require, load, and require_relative. Editing a test
file will re-run all test cases in that file, but editing
a dependency of a single test will only re-run test that
use that functionality. Future work may introduce finer-
grained logic.

Debut (and rename) "qa auto" as "qa watch". This functionality is
available on any qa test run command. For example:
  qa minitest -watch

Globs used by the -watch option support {foo,bar} style
expressions (in addition to * and **), so you can do obscene things
like:
  qa test-unit -watch 'test/{unit,functional}/**/test*.rb'
Note the single quotes so the shell doesn't expand the pattern
and prevent the filesystem watcher from discovering new tests
that fit the pattern.

Split -warmup into -warmup and -eager-load. This way we can avoid
-eager-load when capturing runtime dependencies, which would
introduce noise. Make -warmup default to true again, so basic
rails tests can pass out of the box with a -jobs value > 1.

Make test filter for rspec deterministic across runs (other
frameworks already had this property). This was required for
-watch functionality.

Add -memprofile and -heapdump command line options to help
diagnose memory usage problems within qa itself. This was
important for getting heap usage low enough for -watch to
be useful on large rails projects like discourse.

Improve support for syntax and load errors during test runs. This
was also important for -watch to be useful in the real word.

Also add automated demo asciicast creation. A decent amount
of work in this behemoth of a change was thanks to iterating
on qa so the demo asciicasts would look reasonable. For example:
- Strip minitest paths from backtraces.
- Refine normal qa run output to be tighter and easier to scan.
- Tweak colors and ordering of snail report.
- Fix test seeding to actually generate different values each
  qa run, discovered while trying to generate interesting data for
  a `qa flaky` demo.
- `qa flaky` output has color and no more cruft.
- `qa flaky` shows error messages in overview.
- `qa flaky` shows relative frequency of each type of error.

Other changes that got sucked into this change and couldn't
escape its gravity well:
- Rename tapjio event types to have more regular, sane names.
- Fix a bug in minitest spec support that caused problems
  for tests that had different but identically named describe
  blocks. Thanks to @halostatue for reporting it!
- Add framework-specific commands, so tab completion works. So
  instead of:
    qa run minitest:test/**/test*.rb
      use
    qa minitest test/**/test*.rb
- Fix hang after ctrl-c of qa run command.
- Enable local variable capture by default on macOS, leave disabled by
  default on Linux (for stability reasons).

Finally, update README.md and include the most basic asciicast.

Don't die on syntax errors

QA now treats syntax errors like test errors. This
makes it easier to use on a code base that's
actively being edited. This behavior will be most
useful when combined with (still experimental)
`qa auto` functionality.

Also fix bad timestamps in TAPJ stream. On some
versions of Ruby, we use a monotonic clock that
needs processing before it can be converted to
a date.

commit_list.message:
Fix error and TAPJ stream handling

Better handle errors that require cleanup and unexpected
shutdown of workers. This addresses all known scenarios where
QA would hang instead of exiting.

Also fix improper partial use of a buffered Reader. This
addresses the flaky behavior seen sometimes with an error
message about a test exiting without emitting all expected
events. What was actually happening is the buffered Reader
used for reading the initial token would over-read the line
and the JSON decoder would essentially skip to the end of the
stream. The fix is to keep using the same buffered Reader for
future JSON parsing.

commit_list.message:
Add basic flaky test detection

Using the same -archive-base-dir option with `qa run ...` and
`qa flaky ...` commands will generate a report of which tests
have both succeeded and failed. Additional work is likely
required to properly augment the archived TAP-J streams with
data about specific revisions.

Algorithm for flakiness detection:
- Find all tests that, for a given revision have both passed and failed
- Fingerprints the failures using:
  - the class of the failure
  - the line of source code that generated the failure (not line number)
  - the method and file names present in the stack trace (no line numbers)
- Search all results for matching failure fingerprints, even if no
  passing result can be found for that revision.

Also start using testify and rearrange test files to better organize
qa's tests.
